com.futurice.cascade.rest

Class PrioritizedGettable<KEY extends java.lang.Comparable>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.futurice.cascade.rest.PrioritizedGettable<KEY>
  • Type Parameters:
    KEY - should implement toString() which returns only the primary part of the key, not any supplimental data such as the priority used for comparison
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    IGettable<KEY>

    public class PrioritizedGettable<KEY extends java.lang.Comparable>
extends java.lang.Object
implements IGettable<KEY>
    Fetch the highest priority URL available at the last possible moment as the AbstractRESTService is unblocked

    Example to automatically start fetching the highest priority URL from the web as soon as the web is not exceeding current bandwidth concurrency constraints: 

    
 imageFactory = new PrioritizedUrlFactory(10, mostRecentFirstImageUrlComparator);
 imageFactory.onAdd(ALog.NET.getAsync(imageFactory));
 
    
 ..
 
    
 ImageUrl imageUrl = new ImageUrl("http://this.com/image.jpg", -currentTime, ALog.UI(updateDisplay());
 // Fetch sorted by most recently added first split call updateDisplay() from the UI thread
 imageFactory.add(imageUrl);

        Compares this instance with the specified object and indicates if they are equal. In order to be equal, o must represent the same object as this instance using a class-specific comparison. The general contract is that this comparison should be reflexive, symmetric, and transitive. Also, no object reference other than null is equal to null.

        The default implementation returns true only if this == o. See Writing a correct equals method if you intend implementing your own equals method.

        The general contract for the equals and Object.hashCode() methods is that if equals returns true for any two objects, then hashCode() must return the same value for these objects. This means that subclasses of Object usually override either both methods or neither of them.
